16 2021-01-07 discomfort Patient in clinic for chief complaint of possible side effect of the covid vaccine which she receive... Read more
Close
Patient in clinic for chief complaint of possible side effect of the covid vaccine which she received yesterday. She states that she woke up at 0200 with chest tightness, achyness and headache. She rates the discomfort 7/10 last night and improved now to 5/10. She denies any worsening with any type of exertion and states that she can do simple things like take a shower, walk across the room, down the street or even stairs without any worsening. She denies any SOB or chest pain--just feels tight. Doesn't feel like she can't get a full breath or get the air out of her lungs either. She received her first of two doses of the Pfizer vaccine yesterday (4:23pm) and had no difficulty with the injection itself and then 9.5 hours later woke up from sleep with this chest tightness as well as achyness and headache.  She states that she had the exact same symptoms when she had positive covid test back in August of this year with the addition of fatigue which lasted for 5 days. At that time it was not felt necessary to do any further testing nor treat with steroids according to cardiology. She does have history of LV non-compaction cardiomyopathy and her last visit with cardiology was about 2 years ago and she had a normal EKG and echo only showed "mild LV non compaction at the apex" at that time. He did not need to see her again until she is 18 unless she has problems. She states that she generally does very well and other than this tightness she does not have any other significant symptoms.

Approximately 20 hours after vaccination patient felt faint, lost all color and fainted. She was in and out of responsiveness. Patient was transported to the ER. Patient was treated with fluids and discharged after observation. According to patient's mom the EKG and lab work were unremarkable. Patient has fully recovered.

"Pfizer-Bio-Tech COVID-19 Vaccine EUA" : Individual received the Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine. She began to feel dizzy and flushed at 1:00 pm. Her vitals were 82/46, 22, 68, 98% RA at1:00 pm. 16 2021-03-10 tremor Patient received the 1st dose of the Pfizer vaccine on Feb. 17, 2021. On or about Feb. 22 or Feb. 2... Read more
Close
Patient received the 1st dose of the Pfizer vaccine on Feb. 17, 2021. On or about Feb. 22 or Feb. 23, 2021, she began to notice trembling in her jaw. She told me (her mom) about the trembling on Feb. 25. She had just increased her dosage of Venlaxafine on Feb. 21, 2021, so we actually thought that the jaw tremor was due to that. As a result, at the direction of her psychiatrist, we began to taper off the Venlaxafine beginning on March 1. Over time, the jaw tremor was less noticeable. However, on March 10, 2021, patient received the 2nd does of the Pfizer vaccine. The next day, March 11, 2021, the jaw tremor was worse than ever. I can see the tremor - basically, her lower (?) jaw trembles and you can see the trembling in her mouth and chin. It does not cause pain, and she does not have any other symptoms (no chills, fever, body aches, rashes, difficult breathing, etc.). We talked to her pediatrician and to her psychiatrist. Neither one could say what is causing the tremor; perhaps it is the COVID vaccine; perhaps it is the Venlaxafine (she's not all the way off of it yet); perhaps something else. However, given the timing of the tremor, and given that the strength of the tremor seemed to get better but then got worse again the day after the 2nd COVID vaccine shot, I wanted to report it.
16 2021-03-12 numbness Patient was sitting in the observation area. Patient stated that she was feeling "off" and we helped... Read more
Close
Patient was sitting in the observation area. Patient stated that she was feeling "off" and we helped lower her to the ground into a sitting position. She stated that she felt dizzy and we lowered her onto her back and raised her legs onto a chair. 911 was contacted. Patient remained responsive and was able to answer questions throughout. Patient stated that her shoulder felt like it was burning where she received the injection. She also stated that her face felt numb and her lips felt funny (tingling). Patient was still able to breathe and respond appropriately to all questions. Care was taken over by Ambulance service. After speaking with patients mother later in the day, it was determined patient had a vasovagal episode.

16 2021-03-29 tremor, pain in extremity Within 30 minutes after the shot, my daughter had a headache and sore arm. Other than that she was ... Read more
Close
Within 30 minutes after the shot, my daughter had a headache and sore arm. Other than that she was fine until midnight on Monday morning when her tremors increased and spread up from her legs to her torso and arms. The tremors persisted all day Monday even through her cranio-sacral therapy at Medical Center. Her therapist tried to calm down the tremors through frequency specific micro current with no success. Her therapist could tell that her whole system was in "overdrive" which was vastly different than her previous session a week ago. The tremors were so bad that my daughter wanted her wheel chair again. I took a video of her tremors after her therapy session. Her therapist told us to contact her DO, Dr. about it. I did. She was able to crash around 10pm on Monday. On Tuesday, when she woke up around 2:30pm, she still had the tremors but they weren't as severe. We had a telehealth appt with her sleep neurologist, Dr. at 3pm and showed her the video but she doesn't recall ever seeing her tremors in the past. When I spoke to Dr., I shared the video and she was going to discuss it with the therapist as they know each other. My daughter's tremors have never been this bad. She had one major tremor episode in her legs only over 2 years ago which we attributed to her meds at the time; but again, not this bad ever.

16 2021-04-06 unresponsive to stimuli, tremor Patient presented for her first COVID-19 vaccine. Approximately a minute after vaccine was given, sh... Read more
Close
Patient presented for her first COVID-19 vaccine. Approximately a minute after vaccine was given, she was noted to be seated upright in the passenger seat of her car, with head bent forward and eyes open. She was unresponsive, stiff posture, and was placed into a reclined position. She then had some posturing with head turned to the left, no eye deviation or nystagmus, no tonic-clonic movement. Radial pulse was thready, bradycardia was noted, with normal respirations. She was noted to become diaphoretic and pale/ashen color noted to the face and arms. She became responsive within a few minutes, however initially was not able to answer questions clearly. She had no loss of bowel or bladder function. EMS assisted with evaluation. Initial blood pressure 78/31, HR 54, SpO2 100%. EMS then transferred her to the stretcher and she was transitioned from her car to the ambulance. She continued to improve spontaneously with BP 94/61 then 103/60 and HR 86 then 74. SpO2 remained stable at 100%. Skin color improved. She had normal responses to questions, no complaints of headache, dizziness, chest tightness, shortness of breath, numbness or tingling. She had some shaking/voluntary movement of the limbs and body noted, but she could control and stop this voluntarily, no myoclonic or tonic-clonic jerking noted. After syncopal event occurred, mom reported that the patient has a history of syncope routinely with blood draws and vaccines in the past, however this episode was slightly more prolonged and seizure-like activity was different. She has had some jerking movement previously with syncope which lasts 20-30 seconds, different from today's response. No known history of seizure disorder.
16 2021-04-07 numbness Asthma Attack started at 1 pm while seated and attending virtual class. She was under no distress an... Read more
Close
Asthma Attack started at 1 pm while seated and attending virtual class. She was under no distress and was not in any way exerting herself. She described the attack as a feeling of someone sitting on her chest and began to hyperventilate. The color drained from her face and her hands felt numb. Her asthma attacks are generally exercise-induced, so this was highly unusual. She took a dose of albuterol ( 2 puffs with a spacer) and followed her asthma action plan. She laid down and slowed her breathing. 20 minutes later her facial color returned to normal. Two hours later her hands returned to normal. She was disoriented for about 5 hours.

16 2021-04-08 feeling hot Patient received first dose of Pfizer covid-19 vaccine on 4/9/2021 at 1800 with her mother in attend... Read more
Close
Patient received first dose of Pfizer covid-19 vaccine on 4/9/2021 at 1800 with her mother in attendance after consent was acquired. At 1805 patient began to feel hot and nauseous. The patient thought she was going to vomit, so she left her chair in the waiting area to head to the restroom at the back of the store. at 1807, Upon rising the patient became weak in the knees and began to collapse. The patient's mother initially supported the patient and I was called to assist the patient to the floor. The patient was very pale in appearance as she was assisted gently to the floor, avoiding any injury. EMS was called shortly after the event around 1810. The patient remained conscious however was a bit disoriented initially while lying on the floor. The patient recovered quickly, however remained nauseous and complained of feeling hot. Upon questioning the patient, she had not eaten since lunch at school at 1300. The patient was given a cold water and a sprite, of which she had a couple of drinks out of each. The patient was relocated back into a chair at 1815 as she was feeling much better. EMS arrived at 1821. EMS performed a general assessment and a blood pressure check resulting in 130/80. The patient's mother dismissed any further treatment from EMS. EMS exited the building at 1827. The patient and mother waited in the store for a while longer. Both patient and mother exited on their own, denying escort from associates at 1840.

Acute Infarct of R internal capsule and R basal ganglia; Acute Infarct of R internal capsule and R basal ganglia; Left (L) sided motor deficits; L facial droop; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable physician. A 16-year-old female patient received bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, solution for injection), dose 1 intramuscular, administered in left arm on 24Mar2021 (Batch/Lot number was not reported) as single dose for COVID-19 immunisation. Medical history included truncus arteriosus (status post (s/p) right ventricle-to-pulmonary artery (RV-PA) conduit and prosthetic aortic valve s/p automatic implantable cardioverter defibrillator (AICD) placement) and arrhythmias. The patient have no known allergies to medications, food, or other products. The patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19 prior to vaccination. The patient was not pregnant at the time of vaccination. Concomitant medications included sotalol taken for arrhythmias and warfarin. The patient was therapeutic on warfarin (INR 2.68) at admission and has been historically very compliant with medication. On 29Mar2021 14:00, the patient experienced acute infarct of right (R) internal capsule and R basal ganglia as diagnosed (dx) on magnetic resonance imagine (MRI), concerning for (C/f) cardio-embolic etiology in the setting of patient's complex cardiac history. However, cannot rule out other causes of infarct. Left (L) sided motor deficits on exam, L facial droop. Transthoracic echocardiogram (TTE) was unchanged from prior. The patient was hospitalized for the events from 29Mar2021 to 05Apr2021. The patient underwent other lab tests and procedures which included COVID-19 nasal swab test was negative on 29Mar2021 and on 30Mar2021. Therapeutic measures were taken as a result of the events and included treatment with anticoagulation. Outcome of the events was recovered with sequel on 2021. The following information on the batch number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: As there is limited information in the case provided, the causal association between the events and the suspect vaccine BNT162B2 cannot be excluded. Consider also possible contributory effects from patient's pre-existing cardiac history. The case will be reassessed once new information is available. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer drug is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

16 2021-04-21 seizure My daughter has been diagnosed with catamenial epilepsy, and typically only had seizures very sporad... Read more
Close
My daughter has been diagnosed with catamenial epilepsy, and typically only had seizures very sporadically (months apart). However, she recently had a cluster of seizures, which was very atypical for her. I read a news story last night about the vaccine affecting some women by making their period come back after years of not having it. In reviewing my daughter's seizure events, a pattern emerged in relation to her Covid shots: -Dose 1 of Pfizer on March 17, and the worst seizure she ever had was on March 27 (10 days after first Covid shot) -Dose 2 of Pfizer on March 31, and the second worst seizure she ever had was on April 10 (10 days after second Covid shot) Prior to the Pfizer Covid shots, the shortest frequency between seizures was one month, and that was prior to her starting epilepsy medication (Keppra). She was taking her Keppra (morning and night) at 1000 mg twice daily as prescribed, and had not missed any doses when the seizures occurred. We now suspect that the two recent seizures might be adverse reactions to the Covid shots.

An hour after Pfizer vaccine administration, the parents of the 16 year old patient returned to the pharmacy and reported that their daughter was complaining of trouble breathing in the parking lot. FOC and patient were advised to inform PCP and to report this instance when receiving future vaccines. A 16-year-old non-pregnant female patient received BNT162B2(PFIZER BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE), dose 2 via an unspecified route of administration, administered in left arm on 31Mar2021 (Batch/Lot Number: ER8727) as single dose for COVID-19 immunisation. Relevant medical history includes catamenial epilepsy and attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD). Patient had no other vaccines in 4 weeks. Patient had no known allergies. Patient had not had COVID prior to vaccination. Concomitant medications included levetiracetam (KEPPRA) taken at 1000 mg twice daily to help control seizures, start and stop date were not reported and amfetamine aspartate, amfetamine sulfate, dexamfetamine saccharate, dexamfetamine sulfate (ADDERALL) taken for an unspecified indication, start and stop date were not reported. Patient historically took first dose of Pfizer BNT162B2 (Lot number EN6206) on the left arm at age 16 years on 17Mar2021 at 10:30AM for COVID-19 immunisation and experienced worst seizures. Reporter's daughter has been diagnosed with catamenial epilepsy, and has been taking 1000 mg KEPPRA twice daily to help control seizures. The shortest duration between seizures was approximately 1 month, and that was before her epilepsy diagnosis and starting on the KEPPRA. She has recently suffered a cluster of seizures which is atypical for her. Last night, reporter read an article about some women starting their periods after years of not having it soon after receiving the COVID vaccine, so reporter looked back at her daughter's seizure record and noticed a potential link.Patient had her first Pfizer COVID Shot on 17Mar2021, and she experienced her worst seizure ever on 27Mar2021 (10 days after COVID vaccine). On 31Mar2021, patient had her second Pfizer COVID Shot and she experienced her second worst seizure ever on 10Apr2021 (again 10 days after the second COVID vaccine. Again, her daughter has never had seizures occur in such a short duration, with the minimum time between seizures being one month. The adverse reaction resulted in doctor or other healthcare professional office/clinic visit. Patient was treated for the event which is increase in KEPPRA dose to 1250 mg. Patient had not been tested with COVID-19 post vaccination. Vaccination facility was at a public health department. The outcome was unknown. No follow up attempts are possible. No further information is expected.

Aid assessed PT, took vital signs (1256: BP 104/56 laying, HR 70, SPO2 98% on room air, 1303 BP 110/62 laying, HR 87, SPO2 99% RA, 1307: BP 96/58 sitting, SPO2 99%RA, 1311: BP 106/62 sitting, SPO2 99% RA). Treatment: PT was assisted to lay down on cot, water and juice were provided and consumed, cool compress were provided. Psychosocial support provided. Education to PT and mother to monitor for further s/s and to seek out urgent care if more were noted. Outcome: PT's color improved soon after laying down, PT reported "feeling better" after consuming juice and water. PT sat at edge of cot without difficulty, walked down hallway without difficulty. PT medically cleared by EMS at 1223, exited facility with mother in private vehicle.

Fainted; Didn't know if it was a convulsion or a seizure; Shaking; was very anxious; This is a spontaneous report from two contactable pharmacists. A 16-year-old female patient received BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, lot number: EW0167, expiry date: Aug2021), via an unspecified route of administration, administered in the left deltoid, on 30Apr2021 15:30, as 1st dose, single, for COVID-19 immunisation, at a pharmacy/drug store. There were no medical history and concomitant medications. On 30Apr2021 15:30, the patient received the first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine and was very anxious. She wanted her mom to be present. On the same day, 30Apr2021 15:35, five minutes later, the patient was shaking, and she fainted. The reporter did not know if she was having a convulsion or a seizure. A few minutes later, the patient was sitting and becoming more alert. The patient was given water and one dose of Benadryl. The patient's vital signs were checked (unknown result). The reporter talked to the patient's mother and contacted the patient's pediatrician. The events resulted to emergency room and physician's office visits. Later in the evening, the reporter followed up with the mother and she confirmed that the patient was doing well and better. The mother asked the reporter if the patient should get the second dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. The outcome of the events fainted, shaking, "didn't know if it was a convulsion or a seizure" and "was very anxious" was recovering. The reporter assessed the events fainted, shaking, "didn't know if it was a convulsion or a seizure" as serious (medically significant). The reporter considered that BNT162B2 has a causal effect to the adverse events. Follow-up (18May2021: New information received from a contactable pharmacist includes: reporter information, lab data, suspect drug details (vaccination site and vaccination time), event details (onset time provided, outcome updated to recovering, causality and seriousness assessment provided). Follow up attempts are completed. No further information is expected.; Sender's Comments: Based on the available information, and on a reportedly closed temporal association, the company assessed that a reasonable possibility could not be excluded that the reported events (fainted; didn't know if it was a convulsion or a seizure) were related to the suspect product BNT162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE). The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

The patient's medical history was reported as none. Concomitant medications were not reported. The patient had no known allergies. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within four weeks prior to the vaccination. Prior to the vaccination, the patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19. No other medication was received within 2 weeks of the vaccination. On an unspecified date, the patient had a first time seizure a few minutes after having the vaccine. No therapeutic measures were taken as a result of the event. The event seizure did result in an emergency room/department or urgent care visit. Clinical outcome of the event first time seizure a few minutes after having the vaccine was resolved. It was also reported that since the vaccination, the patient had not been tested for COVID-19. Follow up attempts needed. Further information is expected.; Sender's Comments: Based on available information, a possible contributory role of the subject product, BNT162B2 vaccine, cannot be excluded for the reported event of seizure due to temporal relationship. There is limited information provided in this report. Additional information is needed to better assess the case, including complete medical history, diagnostics including EEG and Head CT/MRI, counteractive treatment measures and concomitant medications. This case will be reassessed once additional information is available. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

Close
vomited; nauseous; visibly distressed; hyperventilating; began seizing/visibly having tonic clonic seizure; HR 116/ HR 114; HR 56; RR 30; BP of 141/46; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable nurse. An 18-year-old female patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine, lot number: EW0170), intramuscular, administered in the right arm on 20Apr2021 at 12:45 as a single dose for COVID-19 immunization. Medical history included anxiety from an unknown date and unknown if ongoing. Concomitant medications included fluoxetine hydrochloride (PROZAC) taken for an unspecified indication, start and stop date were not reported. The patient did not have COVID prior to the vaccination. The patient did not receive other vaccines in four weeks. The patient had not been tested for COVID post vaccination. On 20Apr2021 at 12:45, the patient and her father moved into the waiting area with vehicle. According to the patient's dad, the patient began seizing in the car one minute after the vaccine administration. The dad called out to waiting area monitor. At 12:57 the patient was visibly having tonic clonic seizure and was administered with EpiPen in the right Leg. 911 was called. The patient stopped seizing and was awake and confused. She then became AOx4 (oriented to four spheres; time/place/person/situation). The patient visibly distressed and hyperventilating. At 12:59 the patient had tonic clonic movements and seizure again. The seizure lasted less than 15 seconds. The patient then became AOx4 again, distressed, and became nauseous. Heart rate (HR) was 56 and SpO2 was 98%. At 13:00 the patient vomited while sitting up. The patient had not received other vaccinations within 4 weeks. Patient past drugs included chlorhexidine which she experienced allergy: super itchy skin burning and lidocaine injection for local anesthesia. Patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, Batch/lot number: EL1284) in the right deltoid on 06Jan2021 at 09:35 Am for COVID-19 immunization. Second dose on Wednesday on left side and she stated that she had mild side effects low grade fever, body aches and chills on 27Jan2021 evening. No treatment was given for low grade fever, body aches and chills. She reported that she began to feel left sided swelling, tingling, and drooping of her face on the evening of 29Jan2021. She further described that on Friday (29Jan2021) evening her face was super weak, 1st manifestations were the eye and the left side of her face droopy and neck pain. She took 2 BENADRYL at 8:00 pm and went to sleep. At 08:00 AM next morning she took TYLENOL as her jaw and neck were hurting. She mentioned that while driving to work it got aggravated. She called advice line and she was instructed to go to emergency room. She went to emergency room and was diagnosed with Bell's Palsy on 30Jan2021 via physical exam. She has been prescribed steroids and antiviral for now (30Jan2021). Started Saturday (30Jan2021) on 20 mg prednisone daily PO (orally) for 5 days. VALTREX 1 tab PO (orally) 3xday. Erythromycin 0.5% unguent for eye 4X a day for a week. Her primary doctor increased 60 mg daily prednisone and VALTREX for a total of 10 days. And prescribed lubricant eye drops. Outcome of events Bell's Palsy was not recovered while for other events was recovered on an unspecified date in Jan2021. No follow-up attempts are possible. No further information was provided.; Sender's Comments: Based on a compatible temporal relationship, causality between event Bell's palsy and BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE) cannot be excluded. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

Patient reported symptoms of: tachycardia, shakiness, vision changes, tongue numbness and shortness of breath following the first dose of the COVID19 Pfizer-BioNTech Vaccine on 2/5/2021. Patient said that historically has experienced tachycardia and shakiness after getting a flu shot or booster a few years ago. Symptoms reported by patient were enough to suspect potential anaphylaxis, and patient consented pharmacist to administer epinephrine. Patient was then advised by the pharmacist to follow-up with her primary care doctor as soon as possible to report the incident and to discuss the risk versus benefit of the vaccine, whether recieving the second dose would be appropriate for her. Patient returned to assisted living facility for her second dose of the COVID19 Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine on 2/26/2021. Patient said that she discussed the incident with her doctor, was told it would be appropriate to get the second dose despite her reaction and was advised to take "cautious measures". Pharmacist reviewed the patient information and screening questions, discussed the potential side effects and reiterated her risk of experiencing the same reaction with the second dose. Patient stated that she decided on getting the second dose because "her boyfriend is high risk and I'm doing this for him". Patient stated that she decided on getting the second dose because "her boyfriend is high risk and I'm doing this for him". Pharmacist asked patient if she had any questions/concerns or additional information to add prior to getting her vaccine, and patient denied having any at that time. After administering her second dose, pharmacist instructed patient to stay in the observation area for at least 30 minutes and to ask the staff for water given her experience with the first dose. Patient asked pharmacist how common it was for someone to get a reaction from the vaccine, and then mentioned that her family memeber had to drive her to the emergency room after her first dose becuase her throat was "burning", and was told that her throat was "a little swollen" and recieved a second dose of epinephrine at the emergency room. Patient included this information after the fact her second dose was already administered. Approximately 5 minutes after receving her vaccine, the patient reported similar symptoms that she experienced on 2/5/2021: tachycardia, vision changes, shortness of breath and chest tightness. After monitoring patient with no resolvement of her symptoms, patient was then given a dose of epinephrine by the pharmacist, and the paramedics were called in to assess patient and take her to the emergency room.

The client's friend was also in the room. RN stated that she and the friend grabbed the client, held her, and she started responding to their voices within 15 seconds. RN stated she simultaneously called for help. 2nd RN ran down the hallway to grab EMT and 3rd RN called 911. From the Lead's room, Lead RN and Co-Lead RN observed 2nd RN running down the hallway. Leads proceeded to the hallway and observed a cluster of individuals at vaccination station 5. Lead RN & Co-Lead RN arrived at station 5 at 18:42. Leads observed client conscious and sitting in a chair. Thirty seconds later EMT arrived. Leads observed client was pale in color. Client stated she got dizzy, and her eyes got blurry within seconds after the shot was administered. Client stated she was hot and sweaty, but was not experiencing SOB or trouble breathing. Client was alert and oriented times 4. Co-Lead RN opened the window. RN put a wet towel on client's forehead and client was transferred to a zero-gravity chair. Client stated she had eaten and drank plenty food and fluids earlier in the day. At 18:48 client stated she was feeling better. EMT took vitals at 18:50. (BP: 82/54 HR: 42). RN took client's pulse again and stated HR: 76. Client stated she has no known allergies and takes no medications other than birth control. Client also stated she used to take medication for anxiety, but stopped taking the medication 6 months ago. Firefighter EMTs arrived at 18:54 took vitals (BP: 106/74 O2: 99 HR 68) and performed a 12-lead ECG. At this time client stated that she has never given blood because she starts to pass out when she sees blood. She also stated that she passed out 9 months prior when she saw her sister's blood drawn at the hospital. At 18:58 client's color was coming back. She stated she was no longer dizzy and felt better, but was now cold because the window was open, and her jacket had been taken off to perform the ECG. RN closed the window. Firefighters took vitals again at 19:00 with client sitting (BP: 104/70 O2: 99 HR: 70) and standing at 19:01 (BP: 106/70 O2: 99 HR: 72). Client stated she felt much better. Client declined transport to hospital. Lead RN provided client with a Pfizer fact sheet and educated client on the common side effects vs the adverse effects of the Pfizer vaccine. Lead RN instructed her to contact her HCP if the common side effects persisted beyond 2-3 days and to go to urgent care or the ER if she experienced any adverse effects. Lead RN also instructed client to call 911 if she experienced any respiratory issues once she was home. RN walked client to observation room for additional 15-minute surveillance. Client walked with a steady gait.

Information on batch/lot number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: There is a reasonable possibility that the event "feeling like she was going to vomit" was related to BNT162b2 based on known drug safety profile. Based on the temporal relationship, the association between the other reported serious events with BNT 162b2 can not be completely excluded. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

I got worried and went to the ED. I was assessed, diagnosed with facial paresthesia. I was offered an MRI, I declined as I did not feel that I needed it at the time. Provider prescribed 40 mg of prednisone daily for 5 days, valacyclovir 1000mg 3 times a day for 7 days. After starting prednisone facial muscle tightness I was feeling improved, still felt slight numbness more so in the mornings the next 2 days. I took the full course of prednisone, I am no longer feeling the facial symptoms. I stopped taking valacyclovir on day 3, since I felt that the prednisone was what is helping and it was harder to evenly take it 3 times a day.

25 2021-02-03 discomfort, flushing Patient received the 1st dose of the Pfizer COVID vaccine and was being observed for the 30 minute ... Read more
Close
Patient received the 1st dose of the Pfizer COVID vaccine and was being observed for the 30 minute observation due to history of :severe allergic reaction (anaphylaxis) as a child, with unknown etiology. About 20 minutes into the observation period patient began complaining of tightness in her chest and heaviness in her shoulders. respiratory rate = 20 and unlabored; breathing spontaneously with O2 saturation 100% on room air; BP 116/69, Pulse 103 Mentation: Alert Skin: Cool at onset of symptoms, per EMS recommendation, the patient was placed on oxygen 2 liters via nasal canulaO2 saturations remained at 100 %. Patient noted slight improvement of her symptoms after about 15 minutes with oxygen continuing at 2 liters/Nasal cannula. Continued to observe patient for another 10 minutes, after which time the patient began to complain of a scratchy feeling in her throat, swelling around her mouth, itching and flushing of her face. At 19:05, EMS administered 0.3 mg intramuscular, Epinephrine via auto-injector into patient's right thigh. After 5-6 minutes post-Epi administration, the patient reported having relief of symptoms. Vital signs obtained (BP 108/69, pulse 108) and oxygen saturation stable at 100% on room air. Patient was advised, she would need further evaluation in the Emergency Department after receiving the dose of Epinephrine via auto-injector. Patient was advised to be transported via ambulance. Patient declined transport via ambulance. Patient called a friend to give her a ride to the Emergency Department. EMS personnel called report to the ED. Patient was alert, oriented x3 throughout the adverse event and stable upon leaving the clinic at 40 minutes after Epi had been administered. Vaccine providers were notified of the adverse symptoms post vaccine. Patient will follow-up with her primary provider and allergy provider to determine if second dose will be a possibility to receive.

I am a third-year medical student. Since receiving the second dose of the COVID vaccine (Pfizer) on Tuesday 2/2, I have had persistent and worsening muscle spasms of the torso. I presented to the Emergency room on 2/6 due to worsening symptoms and was admitted until 2/7. The neurology team evaluated my condition was not able to make a firm diagnosis. They believe the vaccine has caused a dystonic reaction. I was given benadryl 25mg to continue for one week q6 hours prn. However, benadryl has provided minimal relief. They also strongly recommended that I be seen by a movement disorder specialist at hospital ASAP. However, due to the fact that I have insurance I am not covered for care from hospital. My insurance said they will review the referral which will take another 5-7 business days from today 2/9. As a medical student, I have had to miss one week of clinic rotations and will continue to miss vital medical training as well as my board exam this Friday due to my worsening symptoms. It has created such a negative impact on my life including pausing my medical training, and physically being incapable of driving or performing many of my basic daily activities. I live alone and near hospital. I am urgently requesting if there is anyway CDC can help me, a medical student who has put in her all to fight the pandemic alongside you. I am extremely concerned about my symptoms and the panic that it has created for my family and friends. I hope that a rapid response can help me and my loved ones find some answers during these challenging times.

25 2021-03-04 numbness, discomfort, cold sweat I made sure to hydrate and eat well the day of the vaccine. I have had no allergic reactions to any ... Read more
Close
I made sure to hydrate and eat well the day of the vaccine. I have had no allergic reactions to any medications/ injections in the past and I was not worried about this one. I didn't take any meds beforehand besides my normal morning modafinil. I have no fear of needles. I received the vaccine in the auditorium about 1:25pm. The RN did a fantastic job, went through all of the information, no pain at all with the injection. As I was sitting in my chair for monitoring, a few minutes in I began to feel very uncomfortable. I felt clammy/sweaty and kept shifting my weight in my seat. I didn't want to make a big deal of it at first because I worried it was all in my head. But I became more and more uncomfortable. I laid my head down on the little desk, no help. I closed my eyes, no help. About 10 minutes or so in I decided to ask if they had water available. I slowly got up and walked to the back of the room. I couldn't even get the question out of my mouth before the nurse told me to sit down. Apparently I was white as a ghost. They got a wheelchair and wheeled me to the space behind the auditorium. By then I was starting to feel like my throat was closing and I saw spots in my peripheral vision. It was kind of a blur from there. I tried to take deep breaths. I drank a few sips of water and poured some on a paper towel to wet my forehead (and spilled all over my lap because I was a little disoriented at this point). My BP was 60s/40s and then 60s/30s. A rapid response was called. They moved me to a cart flat on my back with my legs elevated. My fingers and toes were starting to go numb and my lips were apparently blue/ white. After laying for a few minutes in Trendelenburg my BP began to resolve and my breathing started to ease a bit. No further intervention was done by the rapid team. I was taken by the Rapid RN to the ED for monitoring. They eventually pushed the cart into a room and took some vitals and an EKG. They had me stand and move to a wheelchair. I felt horrible but improved from before. They had me sit in a wheelchair in the lobby for a few hours before taking me back and placing an IV and drawing labs (I believe it was 3 hours from the initial reaction). I gave a urine sample. They then put me in a wheelchair and wheeled me back into the lobby for some more time. Then, they wheeled me back to a room where they gave some lactated ringers and a PA and MD saw me. By then my BP and breathing was completely resolved. The MD said he wasn't fully convinced it was just a vasovagal episode because I haven't had issues with vaccines in the past and I was well hydrated and my HR was normal. It partly fit the picture for an allergic reaction/ severe immune response d/t the feeling of throat closing, the BP drop, and the elevated WBCs. They advised that I list the vaccine as an allergy and do not get the second dose, especially since I had COVID back in September.

I have not had it since 2015 until I got vaccinated on 3/29/21 and began to develop BP symptoms on the evening of 4/6/21 (headache on right side of my head/temple, odd sensation on right side of my tongue, almost like I burned it on a hot beverage) but I didn't think anything of it. I have recovered from BP twice before so I am not too worried about having it again. I just think the FDA needs to put out a warning to the public that there may be a correlation between the COVID-19 mRNA vaccines and Bell's Palsy recurrences. I know this is not a coincidence, and my BP relapse was a result of my body experiencing an immune reaction from the vaccine.

I noticed immediately that the shot hurt, and that it was almost as if I could feel both the beginning and end of the needle. This was unusual for me, because I don't usually notice pain with vaccines. (It may also be worth nothing that the vaccine was not as centered on the deltoid as usual; it seemed to be injected in a location more anterior than medial.) 36 hours later, while my arm was above my head doing my hair, I suddenly felt a sharp and painful tingling shoot down my arm, with pins-and-needles and numbness. The sensation reached from the top of my arm down the outside around the elbow and heavily culminated in my hand and fingers, especially pinky finger. This sensation somewhat subsided, but lasted for somewhere between 1 and 2 hours. Since then, I have experienced pain in my elbow, and sometimes hand/palm and shoulder, and weakness in my hand, fingers, and arm in general. I have described all the different feelings of it as the different stages of having hit your funny bone.

Once the patient was done what I could only identify as seizing, she came to and I asked her if she new her name and where she was. The patient answered correctly and then asked me "Have you had anyone with a reaction like this before?". I answered that I have not personally witnessed a reaction like this before. My technician had 911 still on the phone and they instructed her to stand out front of the store to await the ambulance. A first responding officer came in and asked about the witnesses to the incident then took over for caring for the patient.

25 2021-04-21 numbness, discomfort, migraine I received my first shot on April 6th, 2021, and on April 18th, 2021 I experienced extreme numbness ... Read more
Close
I received my first shot on April 6th, 2021, and on April 18th, 2021 I experienced extreme numbness with slight pain in the fold and shoulder of my arm. I went to the ER and they took a cat scan of my neck and reported back that everything looked normal - the nurse said it was most likely Cervical Radiculopathy. Then the following morning around 11 AM, I experienced very intense burning in my chest starting on the right side, eventually moving to the left encompassing my entire upper chest. I also experienced a very bad migraine, which I am typically used to but this one was more of a pressure headache between my temples that I felt in my ears and jaw. I made the decision to go back to the ER and to a different one this time. The ER failed to administer a Covid-19 test and to take bloodwork - both faults that family and friends in the medical field have pointed out to me. The doctor there had me receive an IV, a chest X-Ray, and an EKG. The X-Ray and EKG were both normal. The doctor had ordered a Covid-19 test but the nurse forgot to administer it before my discharge. In my IV I received Benadryl and Reglan along with typical IV fluids. I was also given Pepcid and Mylanta. At the end of my visit, the doctor concluded that he thought it was my acid reflux acting up - gastroenteritis. I went home and continued to experience chest burning, tightness, occasional numbness/pains in my body, and very, very bad headaches. On top of that, I could barely swallow - it felt as if my throat was closing. I took Pepcid and Tums and neither really did anything. After seeing a Cardiologist this same week, they ordered an Echocardiogram and routine bloodwork (metabolic panel). I will also be following up with a GI, and I received a Covid-19 test today and am awaiting the results. It is possible I contracted Covid before my shot, but it is also possible that I am having a delayed reaction to my first vaccination as well. Who knows.

25 2021-05-24 numbness After receiving my second dose, I was seen by my primary doctor for suspected Celiac disease (which ... Read more
Close
After receiving my second dose, I was seen by my primary doctor for suspected Celiac disease (which came back positive). I had a strange medical episodes during the bloodwork (April 15th) that they originally assumed was anxiety. Symptoms were shortness of breath, lightheadedness, and loss of feeling in extremities. I?m a first responder and did not feel this was anxiety, but didn?t argue and forgot about it until it happened again. I had my second episode on April 20th, and debated going to the ER for it. A third episode on April 23rd did put me in the ER. I proceeded to have more episodes on almost a daily basis after that and started monitoring blood pressure, pulse, blood sugar, and food intake at home (some of my bloodwork levels were off due to the celiac). I purchased a heart rate monitor, a blood glucose meter, and a smartwatch to monitor some of my symptoms. Both devices (monitor and watch) would later flag me as having a suspicious heart rhythm (heart monitor could be for fast/slow rhythm or for arrhythmia, smartwatch flagged me as Afib twice). I could not recreate these results when my husband wore the devices. Episodes could be as brief as 45 mins or last more than 12 hours. I have a high pain tolerance and illness tolerance, and had to leave work several times due to my symptoms (extremely abnormal for me). After several more appointments with my primary doc and another visit to the ER (where they did another EKG, an X-ray, and more bloodwork), things were still coming back inconclusive. After about April 28th, I started having significant chest pain with my episodes. The ER checked me for possible clotting related to the heart issues and my birth control pills. My arrhythmia could not be captured on their devices. My doctor has since diagnosed it as suspected myocarditis (pending more testing). We?ve ruled out all possible things related to my Celiac diagnosis, and can?t seem to find a cause for this. I had a few things I brought to her attention that may be the cause (pinched nerve at chiropractors, covid vaccine) and she says it may be the vaccine, and said I should report it to you.

Patient explained that the symptoms had a sudden onset, but lasted less than 1 minute. Patient has a history of migraines and an allergy to Penicillin. Patient stated that she had a similar reaction after receiving a dose of Benadryl, earlier this year. Patient told EMTs that she had eaten toast, tofu, and salad about an hour and a half prior to coming to the vaccination site, with limited fluid intake. EMTs gave the patient a water bottle to sip on. At 1502 a second set of vital signs were obtained by EMT, while the patient was sitting: blood pressure: 116/68, heart rate: 74, respiratory rate: 15. Pupils were equal, accommodating, and reactive to light. Patient was advised to stay an additional 30 minutes in observation for continued evaluation. Patient stated she "felt better" and all symptoms had improved. Final set of vital signs were taken at 1514 by EMT, while patient was standing: blood pressure: 114/64, heart rate: 72, respiratory rate: 12. Pupils were equal, accommodating, and reactive to light. Skins were warm, dry, and normal. Patient was negative for orthostatic pressures. At 1540, patient stated she "felt normal and that all symptoms were gone." Patient had finished the water bottle provided. Patient was then educated on expected/ adverse reactions, when to follow up with her primary care provider, and the use of V- Safe. Patient ambulated with a steady gait on her own accord out of the facility.
